    <article class="library-chapter">
      <div class="page-head">
        <div class="eyebrow">Chapter V</div>
        <h1>Intervals &amp; Scale Construction</h1>
        <p class="kicker">The distance between pitches — perfect, major, minor, augmented, diminished — and how those intervals build the scales and degrees we name.</p>
      </div>

      <h2>What Are Intervals?</h2>
      <p>Intervals are the distance between two pitches, measured in scale degrees or semitones. Each interval has a specific quality determined by its size (the number of letter names involved) and its quality (perfect, major, minor, augmented, or diminished).</p>

      <h2>Interval Qualities</h2>

      <h3>Perfect Intervals</h3>
      <p>Perfect intervals are the most stable and consonant.</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Perfect unison (P1), perfect fourth (P4), perfect fifth (P5), perfect octave (P8).</li>
        <li>They retain their "perfect" label only at those numbers; raising one a half step makes it augmented, lowering it makes it diminished.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Major and Minor Intervals</h3>
      <p>Major and minor intervals are the most common in music; they define major and minor scales. Major intervals are one semitone larger than minor intervals of the same number.</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Major: <strong>M2, M3, M6, M7</strong>.</li>
        <li>Minor: <strong>m2, m3, m6, m7</strong>.</li>
      </ul>

