      <h3>Augmented and Diminished Intervals</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>An <strong>augmented</strong> interval is one semitone larger than a perfect or major interval. Examples: A1, A4, A5, A8.</li>
        <li>A <strong>diminished</strong> interval is one semitone smaller than a perfect or minor interval. Examples: d2, d3, d4, d5, d6, d7.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Practical Application</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Harmonic analysis</strong> — interval qualities reveal chord structures and the logic of harmonic progressions.</li>
        <li><strong>Melodic analysis</strong> — identifying intervals in a melody clarifies its shape, direction, and emotional content.</li>
        <li><strong>Performance</strong> — accurate interval reading is essential for melodies, harmonies, and improvisation.</li>
        <li><strong>Composition</strong> — composers use intervals to shape melodic and harmonic textures and to convey mood.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Constructing Scales</h2>
      <p>Scales are sequences of pitches arranged in ascending or descending order according to a specific pattern of intervals. The most common types in Western music are major and minor scales, but there are also modes, pentatonic scales, and others.</p>

      <h3>Major Scale</h3>
      <p>The major scale follows the pattern <strong>W–W–H–W–W–W–H</strong>. The C major scale is <span class="mono">C–D–E–F–G–A–B–C</span>: whole steps between C–D, D–E, F–G, G–A, A–B; half steps between E–F and B–C.</p>

      <h3>Natural Minor Scale</h3>
      <p>The natural minor scale follows the pattern <strong>W–H–W–W–H–W–W</strong>. The A natural minor scale is <span class="mono">A–B–C–D–E–F–G–A</span>: whole steps between A–B, C–D, D–E, F–G; half steps between B–C and E–F.</p>

      <h2>Identifying Scale Degrees</h2>
      <p>Scale degrees refer to the position of each note within a scale, indicated by numbers (1, 2, 3 …). Understanding scale degrees is crucial for analyzing melodies, chords, and harmonic progressions.</p>

      <dl class="deflist">
        <dt>Tonic <em>(1st degree)</em></dt>
        <dd>The first note of the scale and tonal center. The most stable note; gives a sense of resolution.</dd>

        <dt>Supertonic <em>(2nd degree)</em></dt>
        <dd>One whole step above the tonic. Often leads to the tonic and has a slightly unstable quality.</dd>

        <dt>Mediant <em>(3rd degree)</em></dt>
        <dd>A third above the tonic. Adds color and character to the melody.</dd>

        <dt>Subdominant <em>(4th degree)</em></dt>
        <dd>A fourth above the tonic. Creates tension and often leads to the dominant.</dd>

        <dt>Dominant <em>(5th degree)</em></dt>
        <dd>A fifth above the tonic. Strong pull toward the tonic; often used to establish the key.</dd>

        <dt>Submediant <em>(6th degree)</em></dt>
        <dd>A sixth above the tonic. Adds richness and depth.</dd>

        <dt>Leading Tone <em>(7th degree)</em></dt>
        <dd>A half step below the tonic. Creates tension and resolves strongly to the tonic.</dd>
      </dl>

      <h3>Practical Application</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Melodic analysis</strong> — identifying degrees clarifies melodic function within a piece.</li>
        <li><strong>Chord progressions</strong> — degrees are used to build chords and understand their relationships within a key.</li>
        <li><strong>Improvisation</strong> — knowing the degrees lets improvisers navigate the scale and complement the underlying harmony.</li>
      </ul>

